     Government shutdown The AP has journalists around the country covering the shutdown of the federal government.  What questions do you have for them? 


 As  the government shutdown  enters its fourth week — on track to become among the longest in U.S. history — millions of Americans are bracing for health care sticker shock while others are feeling the financial hit. Economists have warned the federal closure, leaving most of the 2.4 million-strong federal workforce without pay, will shave economic growth by 0.1 to 0.2 percentage points per week. 


















 There are few signs of any end to the stalemate. Republicans say the Democrats are holding the government hostage, beholden to far-left demands to provide billions of dollars in health care subsidies.  



